4.8:
What I have always seen holds:
the ones who farm trouble harvest it;
those who seed wickedness reap a full crop of it.

4.10:
The mighty lion still roars;
the fierce lion still lifts its voice —
but even the cubs' teeth are already broken.

4.20:
'In less than a day they can be shattered —
and no one marks their passing;
they are simply gone.'

5.4:
His children find no refuge;
they are ground down at the gates of justice
with no one to help them.

5.5:
Famine cleans out the fool's harvest;
strangers grab his crops out of the briars;
the thirsty swallow up everything he saved.

6.4:
The Almighty's arrows are in me and stuck there;
my whole spirit is drinking down their poison.
God's terrors are drawn up in battle order against me.
